[normal]The process of academy conversion does not encourage formal consultation with stakeholders until too late in the process.
[normal]  According to Department for Education rules
[normal] (
[normal]http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/leadership/typesofschools/academies/b00229234/becoming-an-academy/consultation
[normal] )
[normal], 
[normal]Governing Bodies are supposed to consult informal
[normal]ly with 
[normal]stakeholders
[normal] before making
[normal] a Resolution to become an academy. 
[normal]  
[normal]Whether these informal c
[normal]onsultations actually happen
[normal] before Resolutions are passed is unclear.  Formal consultations do not take place until
[normal] after the Secretary of State has given perm
[normal]ission for conversion to go ahead, academy trusts 
[normal]have been established
[normal] and companies registered with Companies House
[normal].   
[normal]This gives the impression 
[normal]conversion is a done deal.  The Governing Body 
[normal]decide
[normal]s
[normal] who to consul
[normal]t, how the consultation is
[normal] done and the t
[normal]imescale
[normal].
[normal]  This suggests 
[normal]Governing Bodies can get away with minimal consultation.
[normal]7
[normal] 
[normal]There should be a statutory requirement for consu
[normal]ltations to take place before 
[normal]Resolution
[normal]s to convert take
[normal] place.  This requirement should also lay down who is to be consulted, how it is to be done and for how long.
