[normal]14 This case study shows the academy conversion programme can encourage local authorities to 
[normal]avoid all but statutory duties to 
[normal]schools, can encourage schools to join academy chains
[normal] which may not be in the 
[normal]best interests
[normal] of pupils nor value-for-money 
[normal]and makes it difficult for local authorities to manage the supply of school places.  Local authorities can no longer commission their own schools – there is a presumption that new school
[normal]s will be academies or free schools.  Yet the National Audit Office 
[normal]2013 (
[normal]http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book-Copy.p
[normal]df
[normal] ) found 
[normal]half of areas where the need for extra school places was high or sever
[normal]e
[normal] received no applications 
[normal]from free school proposers.   L
[normal]ocal authorities have to tout around for chains or sponsors to set up schools
[normal] when new provision is required
[normal].
[normal]The 
[normal]role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands
[normal]15 
[normal]I
[normal]n the event of an Academy failing, th
[normal]e Department for Education
[normal] allocate
[normal]s
[normal] a new sponsor to take over the particular institution.
[normal]  The same is true if an academy chain wants to close
[normal] an academy
[normal].    The choice of sponsor/
[normal]academy chain 
[normal]would not be a Local Aut
[normal]hority decision but would be imposed by the Department for Edu
[normal]cation.  I
[normal]t appears, then, 
[normal]academies are in the gift of the Secretary of State.  This can pave the way for future take-over by for-profit education providers to 
[normal]run
[normal] English academies.
[normal]16 The Regional Commissioners being recruited are supposed to 
[normal]authorise new sponso
[normal]rs.  It’s unclear by what criteria the Comm
[normal]issioner will judge prospective sponsors
[normal].   Neither is it clear how the Commissioners, especially those working part-time, will be able to adequately support and intervene failing academies over a much wider area 
[normal]than any local authority.  Local authorities are much better placed to support and challenge local schools than remote bodies.
[normal]The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations 
[normal]operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in su
[normal]pport for schools at this level
[normal]17
[normal] 
[normal]Local authorities should be the “middle tier” between the Secretary of Sta
[normal]te and individual schools.  They h
[normal]ave 
[normal]local knowledge.  Their responsibilities should be towards all the area’s schools whatever their structure: to p
[normal]romote co-operation between 
[normal]schools
[normal]; to ensure individual 
[normal]schools do not act in their own interests to the
[normal] detriment of other schools and particular children; 
[normal]to monitor schools admission criteria to ensure they adhere to the Schools Admission  Code; 
[normal]to intervene and support 
[normal]struggling school
[normal]s
[normal]; to ensure academy chains are not using their monopoly to impose pa
[normal]rticular methods or resources on their acade
[normal]mies and denying heads the 
[normal]freedom they had when they were local authority schools, and to have access to the financial records of academies to ensure there is no misuse of public funds (e
[normal]g Priory Federation 
[normal] 
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/government/news/media-statement-in-relation-to-the-priory-federation-of-academies-trust
[normal] 
[normal]) or nepotism (eg Kings Scien
[normal]ce Academy
[normal] 
[normal]http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/i/kings%20science%20academy%20investigation%20report.pdf
[normal] 
[normal]).
